Did you mix the numbers, or had a typo? Because you say that where you're at 
at the moment (Vineland, NJ) the price of gasoline is cheaper than where you 
live. ($2.19 vs. $2.69).

>
>     On the job front, it sounds like things are moving very slow for you.
> I'd say you should still persist in making as many contacts as you can.  My
> hunch is that you would probably fit best into a small company where their
> needs happened to be compatible with what you have to offer, but it might
> take a while to find that company.

Yes, I was told that you don't find jobs from newspaper job ads (where they 
are flooded with resumes) but rather mainly from contacts. Recently I also 
enrolled in an HR agency my friend recommended, and I heard from them a lot 
on various matters, and also got my resume sent to several companies and had 
some job interviews.

As for the small company, there are companies of all sorts of sizes in Israel. 
Many small or start-up companies tend to be run by people without much 
experience or knowledge in software and worker management. As a result they 
are often notorious for having bad management, crazy working hours, and 
sub-standard working conditions. There are various exceptions naturally. The 
larger a company is, then usually this situation is better as far as the 
grunt employee is concerned. 

I heard of other opinions regarding what to do. A certain "brian d foy" (a 
well-known Perl guru) said in his blog that software companies are basically 
looking for people who will do what they tell them to do, who will be 
specialized in a certain area, and not think too much outside the box. Thus, 
programmers who have had extensive involvement in the open-source movement 
will not usually be good candidates for them. (And I am such a case). Thus, 
such developers should realize that once they are independant, they should 
remain independant.

Paul Graham (http://www.paulgraham.com/) recently raved about a theme of 
university students or graduates starting their own start-up comapnies in 
several of his essays. I'm not that keen on starting my own company because:

1. Managing companies is a lot of hassle. I tend to become nervous and anxious 
very easily. Doing voluntary work, studying or working as a grunt programmer 
is bad enough, but trying to manage something seems like that I won't be able 
to stand one minute of.

2. Right now, there's a lot of demand for clueful Linux programmers in Israel. 
It is the right time to become employed, and not a very right time to look 
for employees.

3. I have some ideas but they are not particularly good. 

4. Making money out of marketplace (or so called "shrinkwrap" software) is 
difficult. Both commercial software and open-source software (and all the 
rainbow in between) have their own difficulty in trying to make a living out 
of.

A better idea perhaps would be to become a consultant-slash-contractor. I 
forgot to mention that Intel Haifa contacted me about consulting for them 
regarding the Subversion version control system. This is due to them seeing 
me mentioned in various contexts about it. (I have written about it and to a 
lesser extent contributed to it in various places). Eventually they found 
someone else, who also had a contractor status from the government (I happen 
to know him very well), and he's consulted for them for one session. He told 
me that maybe I should understand that I can earn such status by directing my 
open source work to such venues, so people will know and hear about me and 
would like to hire me as a consultant. (Lately, I've been doing small amounts 
of work on many projects.)

