>
> <<The Ironic thing is that the Gaza strip is not considered part of the
> Israeli Fatherland according to religious Jewish tradition.>>
>     That's a new "fact" to me.  Hadn't been aware of that.  Can you tell me
> this:  During the British mandate period, was there much Jewish population
> in Gaza?  Or was it populated almost exclusively by Arabs?

Well, there were probably various settlements in the vicinity of Gaza. The 
Region occupied by the Philistines in the Bible also included such ancient 
and modern cities like Ashdod, Ashkelon, Gath (now Qiriath-Gath), etc which 
are part of territorial State-of-Israel at present. So I suppose their status 
in regards to Land-of-Israel is similar.

In any case, the Gaza strip was conquered by Egypt and as a result its people 
were evacuated during the Israeli war of independence. The settlers came 
after Israel has re-conquered the strip in the Six Days War. I should note 
that when the Peace agreement with Egypt was signed, the Egyptians got Sinai 
back (albeit as a territory in which they cannot put any troops in), but 
refused to get the Gaza strip back, claiming it belonged to the Palestinians. 

Another thing to note is that many of the pre-Independce Israeli settlers were 
not religious, but rather believed that Jews were a people. There was a large 
number of Socialists among the many immigrants to Israel. (which is still 
evident in the Israeli political map). 

