Hmmm... Interesting. The First Crusade (as well as later happenings such as 
Saladin, etc.) were covered in my junior high school's history book, which 
I've read almost fully out of interest.

In any case, this reminds me - did you eventually buy Julian Jaynes' book 
about "The Origins of Concsiousness in the Breakdown of the Bicameral Mind"? 
I can point you to a few summaries:

1. Neo-Tech summary - http://www.neo-tech.com/neotech/discovery/nt3.html. Not 
bad, but Neo-Tech oriented, and so heavily biased. It also doesn't mention a 
lot of evidence and facts brought in the book, which present the foundation 
for the book's arguments.

2. Wikipedia:

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Origin_of_Consciousness_in_the_Breakdown_of_the_Bicameral_Mind

Short URL - http://xrl.us/gxwx

Somewhat laconic, but more Neutral Point-of-Viewish.

---------

Right now I've started to read Jared Diamond's "Guns, Germs and Steel". It 
tries to explain how since the Ice Age, different parts of the Earth Human 
Populace evolved differently because of environmental differences. (like 
geographical, or bio-geographical). My father has read it and raved about it 
considerably.

I should note that according to some things my father told me about the book, 
it seems like the author is wrong in some places. Among else, he claims that 
religion was a tool devised by the leadership to justify wars, a claim which 
doesn't hold water, according to Julian Jaynes theory. In some cases, what my 
father said from it was very enlightening, nevertheless.

Have you read it yet?

